The Lewis dot structure for carbon dioxide (CO₂) involves carbon (C) and two oxygen (O) atoms. Carbon has 4 valence electrons, and each oxygen has 6 valence electrons, making a total of 16 valence electrons for the CO₂ molecule. The structure is arranged to satisfy the octet rule for each atom while ensuring the total number of valence electrons does not exceed the available count.

In CO₂, the carbon atom is in the center, with double bonds connecting it to each oxygen atom. This uses all 16 valence electrons, with each oxygen and the carbon achieving an octet.

Here's the LaTeX code to depict the Lewis dot structure for CO₂:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{chemfig}

\begin{document}

\chemfig{O=[:30]C=[::-30]O}

\end{document}
```

This code will generate a diagram showing the double bonds between the carbon and each oxygen, illustrating the shared electron pairs in the molecule.
